Both statements are true. They describe two steps of the same thing, but beginners think they are different. They are not.

Let’s walk through it logically.

Step-by-step: what happens when you run a program

Suppose you open Google Chrome.

Step 1 — Program is on disk

Chrome is stored on your hard disk / SSD as a file.

At this stage it is just a program, not a process.

Disk → chrome.exe
Step 2 — OS allocates memory

When you double-click Chrome:

The Operating System decides how much RAM Chrome can use.

Example:

Total RAM = 8 GB
Chrome gets = 2 GB

This step is called memory allocation.

The OS reserves part of RAM for the program.

Step 3 — OS loads program into memory

Now the OS copies the program from disk into that RAM space.

Disk → RAM

This is called loading the program into memory.

Step 4 — CPU starts executing

Once the program is in RAM, the CPU executes the instructions.

Now Chrome becomes a process.

So the full flow is
Program on disk
      ↓
OS allocates RAM
      ↓
OS loads program into RAM
      ↓
CPU executes program
      ↓
Program becomes a process
Example 1 — Opening Word

You open Microsoft Word.

What OS does:

Allocate RAM for Word

Load Word program into RAM

CPU starts executing Word

Now Word is a running process.
